---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SITE_AUTHOR, GITHUB_URL } from '../consts';
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead title={`About — ${SITE_AUTHOR}`} description="Former Navy AEGIS technician building ML systems for defense applications." />
  </head>
  <body>
    <Header />
    <main>
      <div class="about-header">
        <h1>About</h1>
      </div>

      <div class="about-body">
        <p>
          I spent several years in the Navy as an AEGIS Fire Control System (FCS) and Operational Readiness Test System (ORTS) technician. I stood watch as a Combat Systems Officer of the Watch
          and ran a work center responsible for the sensors and weapons systems at the
          heart of shipboard air defense. I know what a radar track looks like when
          something is wrong — before anyone calls it out.
        </p>

        <p>
          After leaving the Navy I completed an MS in Statistics, with coursework in
          real analysis, graduate linear algebra, and stochastic processes. I am now
          building toward a role in defense AI — specifically the application of
          modern ML to the kinds of sensing and tracking problems I worked on operationally.
        </p>

        <p>
          This blog documents that work in public. The primary project is an
          end-to-end radar track anomaly detector — simulated SPY-1D track data,
          Kalman filter baselines, sequence models, and a full MLOps pipeline.
          Every post is written to be technically rigorous and grounded in the
          operational context that makes the problem worth solving.
        </p>

        <h2>Background</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>US Navy — AEGIS FCS / ORTS Technician</li>
          <li>Combat Systems Officer of the Watch (CSOOW)</li>
          <li>Work center supervisor, sensors and weapons systems</li>
          <li>MS Statistics</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Current Focus</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Radar track anomaly detection — simulation, Kalman filtering, sequence models</li>
          <li>PyTorch, MLflow, Docker, DVC, FastAPI</li>
          <li>Defense AI applications — target tracking, sensor fusion, anomaly detection</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Code</h2>
        <p>
          All project code is on <a href={GITHUB_URL} target="_blank">GitHub</a>.
          The primary repository is
          <a href="https://github.com/W-DeAngelis/aegis-track-anomaly" target="_blank">
            aegis-track-anomaly
          </a> — an end-to-end ML pipeline for radar track kinematic anomaly detection.
        </p>
      </div>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>

<style>
  .about-header {
    padding: 2em 0 1em 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    margin-bottom: 2em;
  }
  .about-header h1 {
    font-size: 2em;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .about-body {
    max-width: 640px;
  }
  .about-body p {
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }
  .about-body h2 {
    font-size: 1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-top: 2em;
    margin-bottom: 0.75em;
    font-weight: 700;
  }
  .about-body ul {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 1em 0;
  }
  .about-body ul li {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    padding: 0.3em 0;
    padding-left: 1.2em;
    position: relative;
    font-size: 0.95em;
  }
  .about-body ul li::before {
    content: '—';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--accent);
  }
</style>
